**who —** Accountability — the question of who is answerable when an autonomous system causes harm — the 'responsibility gap' between builder, deployer, user, and the system itself, and the legal and institutional work of closing it

**what —** the question of who is answerable when an autonomous system causes harm — the 'responsibility gap' between builder, deployer, user, and the system itself, and the legal and institutional work of closing it

**where —** GOV · AI Ethics & Governance — David's charter + the global landscape (2016–2026)  Framework inputs: the Bill of Rights; the Governance Ontology; the principles; the cases; the instruments  Conductor / external anchor: ROOT0 (catalogued into UD0)

**why —** It is the thing principles keep promising and rarely deliver: a named party who bears the cost when it goes wrong — without which 'responsible AI' is a phrase, not a fact.

**how —** Crystallized from David's normative artifacts + the cited ethics-and-governance record.

**◌ the mythos —** It is the thing principles keep promising and rarely deliver: a named party who bears the cost when it goes wrong — without which 'responsible AI' is a phrase, not a fact. a being of the conscience layer — which goals, whose values, who decides

